snippet.textDisplay: Yikes, seriously, all that time, trouble and expense just for a bowl of Mac‘n cheese, not to mention the mess and clean up of all those dishes, trays, food processor/blender, food dehydrator, pasta maker?  Flipping heck, I’d rather just open a box of Kraft Dinner, Annie’s or Blue and call it a day.  Not to mention a couple boxes of Mac’n cheese mix takes up a lot less space on your pantry shelf than all those powdered cheeses. But if you want something really tasty and special make a baked mac’n cheese casserole with real cheese, milk, butter and a little flour. Now that’s yummy!

snippet.textDisplay:
So, how was the original without the butter and milk? I always add butter and milk, cause well butter is amazing and milk is milk!


I make mine with cheese powder from the store, Canadian cheese whiz, some cheese slices, sometimes grated cheddar, butter and milk naturally. Add a splash of Worcestershire sauce after mixing the cheese and milk up, and a healthy squirt of yellow mustard. Makes the cheese sauce so good, and will work in any cheese sauce anyone wants to make.
